# Genetic tag pattern (optional convention)

This rule activates only in files that already use the genetic-tag convention
(`AI_INDEX.md`, `INDEX.md`, anything under a `genes/` folder, project
`CHANGELOG.md`, `PLAN*.md`). If your codebase does not use these files it
stays dormant.

## Form

`<domain>.<subsystem>.<role>.<generation>`

- `<domain>` — a top-level section of your product (e.g. `billing`, `auth`,
  `ui`, `infra`, `docs`).
- `<subsystem>` — a named area inside that domain (e.g. `checkout`,
  `session`, `navigation`).
- `<role>` — the role this module plays (e.g. `entrypoint`, `validator`,
  `schema`, `mapper`, `gateway`).
- `<generation>` — `gen1`, `gen2`, … Bumped **only** when the semantics are
  replaced; a refactor inside the same semantics stays on the current gen.

### Examples

- `billing.checkout.gateway.gen2` — a second-generation checkout gateway.
- `ui.navigation.decision_tree.gen1` — a first take on navigation decisions.
- `docs.plugins.capability_matrix.gen1` — first version of a plugin catalog.

## When to introduce a tag / local index

- **Many integration points** (≈ 10+ or multiple entry modules) → consider
  a local `AI_INDEX.md` that lists hot files, the genetic tag, and sideways
  references to related subsystems. Also reference it from any central
  "navigation map" your project keeps.
- **Non-trivial subsystem with non-obvious boundaries** (≥ 1 file + README
  with surprising interfaces) → a minimal `AI_INDEX.md` is still worth it;
  agents find it quickly via the tag.

## Generation bump rules

- Bump `gen<N>` only when replacing semantics. A performance rewrite of the
  same semantics stays at the current generation.
- When `gen2` lands, mark `gen1` as **legacy** wherever it is referenced and
  in its own file so future readers follow the right trail.

## Why this pattern

- Tags like `billing.checkout.gateway.gen2` are **semantic addresses**: they
  tie task meaning (checkout gateway) to a row in your navigation index and
  to a subtree of related modules — not to a folder name that can change.
- Use them in commit messages, PR descriptions, and agent summaries when
  that reduces ambiguity. ("bumps billing.checkout.gateway to gen2" is
  clearer than "refactors checkout module".)

## Not required

This is an opt-in convention. If your project does not have an index/genes
tradition, this rule stays out of your way — the globs above don't match
anything in a typical repo.
